item.label: Dura/Arachnoid
item.name: Dura_Arachnoid
item.description: The dura & arachnoid refers to a combination of the two outer layers of the meninges, i. e. dura mater and arachnoid mater.

item.label: Denticulate ligaments
item.name: Denticulate ligaments
item.description: The denticulate ligament is AKA the dentate ligament. It is a serrated, shelf-like extension of the pia mater on each side of the spinal cord that serves to stabilize the cord within the vertebral canal. Each of the 21 pointed processes attaches to the arachoid/dura midway between the roots of the spinal nerves.

item.label: Spinal cord
item.name: Spinal cord
item.description: The spinal cord is that portion of the central nervous system that extends from the medulla to the conus medullaris. It consists of 31 segments (8 cervical, 12 thoracic, 5 lumbar, 5 sacral, 1 coccygeal) and has enlargements at the levels serving the limbs (C5 - T1 and L2 - S3).

item.label: Spinal nerve roots
item.name: Spinal nerve roots
item.description: Spinal nerve roots include the dorsal and ventral roots which join with one another to form the spinal nerves. The dorsal roots are afferent or sensory nerve fibers carrying information to the spinal cord while the ventral roots are efferent or motor nerve fibers carrying information from the spinal cord to muscles, glands and other effector organs. Upon entering or exiting the spinal cord, the roots are subdivided into rootlets.

item.label: Anterior spinal vessels
item.name: Anterior spinal vessels
item.description: The anterior spinal artery and vein travel along the anterior or ventral median sulcus of the spinal cord.

item.label: Radicular artery, Adamkiewicz
item.name: Radicular artery
item.description: The radicular arteries branch from the segmental arteries of the thorax and abdomen. These vessels travel to the spinal cord via the dorsal and ventral roots and anastomose around the spinal cord with arterial branches coming from the anterior and posterior spinal arteries to form the vasa corona. In the area of T12 usually on the left side, one of these radicular branches is particularly large and may supply the entire lumbosacral spinal cord; it is known as the great radicular artery or the Artery of Adamkiewicz.
